TRIP COMMENTS: This was a Central Valley Birding Symposium pontoon boat outing along Pardee Reservoir led by John Luther and accompanied by two members of the East Bay Municipal Utility District staff.  This count differs slightly from a report filed earlier from another member of the outing who took the actual group count.  Unfortunately not everyone wished to be included in the initial report, or were mistakenly left off the shared listing.  The morning was sunny, with an early chill in the air, which eventually subsided as the day progressed.  We all felt a slight disappointment in the lack of birds observed as from previous years, and felt it may have been due to the unusually warm temperatures experienced this autumn.
SPECIES COMMENTS: We saw one adult, Bald Eagle at various points along our trip offering excellent views.

TRIP COMMENTS: MBC with Robin and Richard Wolcott. We did a point count near the start of the gravel section of Abel Road before we traveled down the gravel section of Abel Road. Massive numbers of birds were noted all along the road as we later drove east. The point count was just a start in denoting the species of the daunting number birds present in the area.

Road was in horrendous shape when I arrived--very muddy and being graded.  I powered through stretches where I probably shouldn't have, but made it through OK.  On my return leg westbound, the grading had improved the road, but still quite muddy.  I ran into Dale Rubach while there.

Weather: overcast, brief barely perceptible drizzle; light E wind; temperature about 57 F.  Tide: falling from near mean sea level; for Angel Island west the predicted height of the tide fell from about 2.8 ft. to about 2.3 ft. during these observations.  Mean sea level is 3 feet.
SPECIES COMMENTS: perched in separate eucalyptus trees to the north; one appeared to be the eagle that has been in the area for 2 months; it has a mostly white head and tail.  About 5:30 I saw it attack a flock of coots that were just offshore between the spit and Aramburu Island.  After several unsuccessful passes over the flock, the coots moved in toward the lagoon and the eagle gave up.  It returned to perch in a eucalyptus tree.  The second eagle was mostly brown but it was farther away and the light was not good.  It was gone when the older eagle was on the attack.

TRIP COMMENTS: After a rather long drive over from Ukiah, Brian Daniels and I began a morning of birding along the southern coast of Mendocino County in search of a Trumpeter Swan that had been present outside the small community of Manchester since first reported on 6 February 2016 by Tim Bray.  Although reports had listed this location as the mouth of Brush Creek, it appears form Google Earth that this creek is instead Lagoon Creek and that Brush Creek is located a short distance to the north.  To check this site we parked at the end of Bristol Road and walked up to an unoccupied house that overlooks the lagoon.  After quickly finding the swan, I concluded that I wanted better views, so I worked my way down through the dunes to a closer observation point that was located along the south side of the lagoon.  While I did this, Brian instead worked his way to the west to better see birds offshore, and as such, I missed several of the birds that he saw at this site.  Apart from what was presumably a cover of European Beachgrass on the dunes, the dues had small stands of Coyotebush and where we parked was amid tall Coastal Sage-scrub where as I recall the dominant species was also Coyotebush, but likely with a variety of other native plants.  There were also some small pines along the driveway, but we did not spend much time looking for land birds during a relatively brief stop that concentrated on waterbirds in general and the swans in particular.  There was a 30% cover of high, thin clouds, a trace (<5 knot) breeze from the north, and temperatures that ranged 48-55° F (based on the thermometer in Brian's vehicle).  9:00-10:15 am.----Bobcat - 1 (seen scampering off the road just before we arrived at the end of Bristol Road).

TRIP COMMENTS: The distance and time are for my car, which had Lyann Comrack all day, had Todd McNicholas for most of the morning and all afternoon, and Tom Horner for most of the morning. Tom departed after lunch at the Deli and Todd stayed with Lyann and me through the countdown at the Round Table pizza place in Auburn where the Auburn Audubon Society bought the pizzas for all counters. We purchased our own drinks.---- It was about 30F when we started and 41F when we stopped.  It was sunny all day and there was only a little breeze sometimes.  Bird activity was very slow and many winter visitors from higher elevations were absent from the areas we covered.  I was part of the group that formed this CBC circle in 1980 and have covered my Area 7 in all but two years when I was out of the county.  It is my favorite of all Christmas Bird Count circles.----Highlights were the Bald Eagles, Hooded Mergansers, Western Grebe, Brown Creepers, and Golden-crowned Kinglets. Biggest surprise was finding a flock with at least 50 visible Wild Turkeys and probably more hidden by vegetation.----Each of my four teams found species no other team saw.  Had all been able to count all day, we would certainly found additional species. As a team we produced 83 species for my Area 7. Other participants this year were Craig Swolgaard and Phyllis Wilburn in one area; Dan Kopp, Maureen Geiger and Ken Poerner in another; and Tom Horner and Todd McNicholas for the first two hours of the morning in the private area owned by the man who collects animal fossils and permits my team to cover his property.

Car travel was 4 miles over 30 minutes; walking was 1.8 miles (no duplicated mileage) over 5 hours. Weather was very good, partly cloudy, calm, and temperatures ranging from 44 to 52 F. Many fishermen were actively engaged in fishing the recently reopened waters of the American River. As a result, gulls were flushed from many of their normal sites and numbers were low.--

TRIP COMMENTS:
Joined John Trochet. Red admiral. No rain and calm despite the forecast. We walked from the Farm Center, around some of the rice fields where John found a Glaucous Gull the previous day. We then walked past the equipment pad, down to the Accidental Forest and along the overflow channel (a lot of clambering over and through veg) to the MAPS station at the southeast corner of the Tall Forest. We went by the Shack on the way out. Considered breaking this up into a couple of lists, but we were covering a lot of ground and didn't have time. We probably walked close to 7 miles, but I put 5 to account for back-tracking on the same route at times.

I clearly saw white tail and white head on the dark brown bird as it soared in circles above the angel Moroni. By the time I caught up with mom it was out of sight and she asked if I saw a hummingbird. Later I handed her my binoculars and went to change clothes. She called out for me to look to my left because she saw a large dark bird, which after some discussion could have been another eagle, but I didn't see it because I was busy trying to get a better look at who was visiting the nest on the outside of the restroom wall and thought she was just telling me where the door was or something. She said she thought the large dark bird with hooked beak that she saw did not have a white head. It could have been a younger bald eagle or maybe a golden eagle or possibly the same hawk I saw or another type. She guesses it was at least as big as a red tailed hawk.

SPECIES COMMENTS: I was actually shooting Sandhill Cranes by Desmond Road and Bruceville Road. The weather was hazy not great for photos. I turned the corner onto Desmond Road from Bruceville and looked over east about 150 yards and noticed a big object on a telephone pole.  I stood right at the intrance to the Farm. I thought wow pretty big hawk. I pulled out my binoculars and went holy crap, it's a BALD EAGLE, my first in Sacramento County! What a lucky man I was and was thrilled to the max. I couldn't get a great photo, too far away with my 500mm and my 7D m2, total of 800mm focal length. I watched for about 30 minutes as he tore apart and ate something for breakfast. This photo was cropped way in. Sometimes it's not about the photo, but the experience of seeing such a special bird!

There were three spent condoms at one of the places we stopped, and Kevin pointed out there was usually an energy drink (Rockstar, Monster, Red Bull) can at each stop. We had a good time with some misses but saw several more likely to miss birds.

TRIP COMMENTS: 50 F, 100% cloud cover. I just happened to be in the neighborhood. So, decided to stop. Last time I was at the lake it was nearly bone dry. So, I was shocked and delighted to see water and thousands of waterfowl. However, even though it was overcast, I was looking into the setting sun. It was already dark because of the cloudy conditions, but getting darker by the minute. I simply could not count all of the birds present. Hence, I have to resort to using the dreaded "X" for some species. As far as I can tell, this is the first eBird checklist of this hot spot since I was here on 19 July 2015. I birded from the Highway 152 Call Box. This is a very, very dangerous road. Extreme caution should be used, especially when pulling off to the call box location.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Female on nest that was first discovered by myself and two other birders in 2004. Nest is on private property. The owners are aware of the nest. This is the first time I have put this in eBird. PLEASE RESPECT THIS NEST. DO NOT CROSS ANY FENCES. Even though I have looked many times, this is the first time I have seen her IN the nest this season. The current nest was rebuilt last year when the old nest became too heavy and crashed to the ground. They rebuilt the nest last year, but it was rather flimsy and very late in the season, especially for this pair who are considered an "advanced" pair — nesting early and raising two young every year, but one, since 2004. In the 2015 season, due to the rebuild of the nest, they only fledged one young. Still, that was pretty good. I don't know if they were late in laying this season because they were working late into the season of 2015 raising that youngster, but that could be the case. They rebuilt the nest this year by late November, but nothing was happening, although I occasionally saw them in the area. I have confirmed that they feed primarily on ground squirrels. I actually sat out there and watched them for hours, catching ground squirrels. There are no large bodies of water in the area. So, they are not eating waterfowl or fish. Paicines Reservoir would be the closest body of water. But, it went bone dry in May 2014 during the severe drought. Water in that reservoir is controlled by the county and comes from Hernandez Reservoir. Paicines Reservoir is still bone dry as of today. I'm heading to Hernandez tomorrow. PLEASE RESPECT THIS BREEDING PAIR.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Both young eagles were perched in an oak tree, indicating yet another successful breeding season from the very seasoned pair of adult bald eagles who were first discovered nesting at this location in 2004 (Shearwater, Danzenbaker, Green). This was San Benito County's first-ever, confirmed breeding pair of bald eagles. Despite setbacks during two years, this pair has fledged two young every year  (one year the male was shot dead and no young were raised, and last year, 2015, the nest crashed to the ground as it was so large and heavy. They fledged 1 youngster in 2015 after rebuilding the nest late in the season). The adults primarily feed on ground squirrels (confirmed by Shearwater, pers. obs.)

At 1:10 PM from my deck I observed a very large raptor soaring high above Cole Valley, initially coming from the east over Buena Vista Park. While in view for the next 1-2 minutes, it only flapped a few times and continued gliding S in the direction of Twin Peaks and then out of view.  Very large wingspan and large head and bill.  Mottled white and brown and underparts, with extensive white in the tail and on the belly and underwings. I believe this was a 2nd-year bird.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Oh yeah, best bird of the day for me. This large bird appeared above East Camino Cielo to the east of La Cumbre Peak and soared along the ridge to the west. I saw the bird for a minute or so through 10x binoculars from approximately 50 meters distance. Its size made this an obvious eagle and its wedged tail shape pointed towards Bald instead if Golden. Through binoculars it was clear it had white axillaries, rather than white primaries, further confirming Bald over Golden. The photo shows that it had a brown belly, making this a juvenile. Heck of a nice surprise at this location. ----

Joan Lentz birding class. Clear and unseasonably warm. Lake level very low.  Parked in lot west of the launching pad lot.  Walked west down to near the water's edge by following old Rte. 150 which had been under water for decades but was now exposed.  Although views were distant, we had a nice variety of species.  Noted many Savannah Sparrows and American Pipits in the weedy grasses that now grow between the upland area and the lake shore.  Interesting to note this habitat created by receding lake level, but harbored all these sparrows, the geese, and the harrier.

LOCALITY: Savage Rapids Bald Eagle Nest Site
TRIP COMMENTS: Nest is located on the river left side of the Klamath River, downstream and just around the bend from Savage Rapids.  In year 2016 the nest tree is a dead-topped Douglas Fir.  Nest is placed very near to the top of the tree, with full sun exposure.  (Another active Bald Eagle nest is located close by upstream at the Ladd's Creek confluence.)
SPECIES COMMENTS: Using a spotting scope, we observed the female sitting on nest while the male was downstream hunting.  While we were there, none of the male's hunting attempts were successful and he did not visit the nest.  The stick nest was too deep to observe the tops of nestling heads, so the stage and number of offspring is unknown at this point in time.

TRIP COMMENTS: Birding by kayak from the boat ramp at Basso Bridge to the boat ramp at the Turlock Lake SRA campground. The river flow rate was 170 cfs, a good flow for birding because I did not have to concentrate too much on paddling in tricky currents or water that was too shallow. I saw six salmon (three pairs), two in the first riffle below Basso Bridge and four in a riffle about half way down. Three adult Bald Eagles perched over the river were apparently waiting their return. Weather: partly cloudy, 70-65 degrees F, winds mostly calm or nearly so.

LOCALITY: Success Lake--Tule & Rocky Hill Areas/CA-190 viewing locations
TRIP COMMENTS: Lake Success.  Today I spent a bit of time birding at and around the lake.  I started scoping the lake from the dam pullout along CA-190 and from the Tule Recreation Area, I only did a little birding around the north campground (10:15a–11:15a).  I then birded other locations at the north end of the reservoir before coming back to end my day at the Rocky Hill Area where I briefly looked at the lake again and walked along the entrance road at the spillway area looking for Rufous-crowned Sparrows and looking for the Osprey nest by the dam (14:10–15:00).  The lake is the fullest it's been since the beginning of the drought four years ago.  Much of the riparian areas of the Tule River coming into the lake are flooded and some completely underwater.  Cloudy to mostly cloudy, mostly calm, very recent rain, 58°/69°F.

TRIP COMMENTS: This is one of 6 parts of the Kaweah Christmas Bird Count (CBC) circle covered by Rob Hansen and his party on the 2106 Kaweah CBC.  Rob Hansen, Jose Vera, and Andrew Glazier borrowed a key to California Department of Forestry's Mankin Flat Fire Road earlier today from John Dofflemyer.  After unlocking the gate on the east side of Dry Creek Road, they drove along the toe of Pogue Canyon, around a hill then northeast along the slope above the west side of Greasy Creek until they reached the first sizeable grove of live oaks 3.0 mile's drive from Dry Creek Road.  On the way back out they took a detour south to the cattail pond on the pasture just west of the base of Terminus Dam.  After getting back onto Dry Creek Road, the party returned the key to the Dofflemyer Ranch and then drove south back to Lomitas Drive (Hwy. 216).
SPECIES COMMENTS: This bird, probably a second winter bird, showed so much white on its wing linings that I thought at first it might have been a California Condor!  I quickly realized, because of how much white was visible on the bird's belly that it was an immature Bald Eagle.  It appeared above the same ridge where the Golden Eagles had been about 5 minutes after they flew off to points unknown.

This report is one of 6 parts being submitted today by Rob Hansen to document birds seen on the 2016 Kaweah Christmas Bird Count (CBC).  The same party that birded the northwest portion of the Kaweah CBC circle birded Bravo Lake by walking west-northwest across the [mostly] dry lake bottom from the southeast corner of the lake.  Most of the birds were so distant in the only deep water along the lake's west edge that I was unable (even with my scope) to identify gulls to species.  We included 15 minutes of birding time just west of the lake's west levee as we stopped at 7:45 a.m. to scope 2 adult Bald Eagles in the tallest eucalyptus that grows on the west side of Valencia Boulevard (Road 212).  The birding mileage total refers to 5 miles while driving and one mile as we walked out into the lake bottom and back.
SPECIES COMMENTS: We stopped to scope (and photograph) these 2 adults as they sat together on their traditional perch at the top of the tallest eucalyptus trees on the west side of Valencia Boulevard just west of Bravo Lake's west levee at 7:45.  I saw what was presumably one of these same adults flying over water birds on the open water along the west edge of Bravo Lake at about 9:40 a.m. (and Steve Fesperman saw what was presumably one of these same adults near the Woodlake Wastewater Treatment Pond at about 10:05 a.m. when he drove past en route from Woodlake to Yokohl Valley).

Observed an adult male and female of this species.  The female arrived last year from Santa Catalina Island.  Her patagial tag is ORANGE 97.  She then drove off the female that was paired with the existing male, destroyed their egg and a chick, and attacked the previous female.  ORANGE 97 then successfully paired with the existing male eagle, and now the two have refurbished the nest from last year.  Observed the male fly out twice and return carrying large sticks for the nest.  The female stayed perched on the nest.  The nest is now (second year in this location) a substantial structure in the top of a Eucalyptus tree, easily seen from "Teacup" parking area.  We walked further up along the road and got great views of both birds.  I believe this is the 4th year that nesting has been attempted at this location, and possibly longer.  It's been decades since a Bald Eagle has nested on the mainland in Ventura County, so this nest is significant.

TRIP COMMENTS: Joan Lentz's birding class.  We drove from the Carpinteria Bluffs, where we carpooled to Lake Casitas County Park.  After entering the park, we went all the way to the southwest corner, parking at the "Teacup" area.  Then we walked further down the road and climbed the little hill so we could see the eagle nest and observe that portion of the lake.  Then we retraced out steps and got back in our cars & drove down to the area where the docks have been moved to.  We could get even closer by walking northeast of the boat docks along a trail that  paralleled the lake.  This is where all the Gadwall were seen, and we could get close to many of the grebes, but were not able to sometimes differentiate the Clark's vs. Western species if the birds were too far away.  The day was cloudy, cool, rain threatening.  Perfect conditions.
